                You're a nitrogenous base on DNA! Look around - where do you think you are in the cell?
            </div>
            
            <div class="choices">
                <button class="choice" onclick="makeChoice(1, false, 'The cytoplasm is where proteins are made, but DNA lives elsewhere!')">Cytoplasm</button>
                <button class="choice" onclick="makeChoice(1, true, 'Exactly! DNA is safely stored in the nucleus, protected by the nuclear envelope!')">Nucleus</button>
                <button class="choice" onclick="makeChoice(1, false, 'Mitochondria have some DNA, but most genes are in the nucleus!')">Mitochondria</button>
            </div>
            
            <div class="feedback" id="feedback-1"></div>
            
            <div class="description" id="description-1">
                <h2>üéØ Welcome to the Nucleus!</h2>
                <p><strong>Perfect choice!</strong> You are a <strong>nitrogenous base</strong> on a DNA strand in the nucleus! Think of DNA as the cell's recipe book üìö. Each recipe (gene) tells the cell how to make a specific protein. Just like a cookbook stays in the kitchen while you make copies of recipes to share, DNA stays safely in the nucleus while copies (mRNA) are made to carry instructions out to the ribosomes!</p>
                <p>üîç <strong>Fun Fact:</strong> If you stretched out all the DNA in one human cell, it would be about 6 feet long!</p>
            </div>
            
